## Wedding Band Pairing for a Rose Gold Pear Diamond Ring

The pear diamond creates the same band gap challenge in rose gold as in any other metal — the curved belly does not sit flush against a straight band, leaving a visible space between the two rings.

**Three pairing strategies for rose gold pear rings:**

**Contoured rose gold band:** A band shaped to mirror the pear belly sits flush against the stone with no gap. Match the gold karat exactly — 14k rose gold engagement ring with 14k rose gold band. Mismatched karatages in rose gold are more visually noticeable than in yellow gold because the copper content difference creates a distinct color shift. Custom contoured bands add approximately $400–$900 to the band cost.

**Thin straight band with deliberate gap:** A thin (1.5–2mm) plain rose gold band worn with a deliberate gap between the two rings. In rose gold, the gap between a blush metal band and the curved stone base can read as an intentional floating effect — the pear appears to lift slightly above the band. This approach works best with a point-up oriented pear and a modern aesthetic.

**Eternity or pavé band on the outer side:** Wearing the wedding band on the outer side of the engagement ring (toward the nail) avoids the gap entirely while adding diamond coverage to the stack. A slim rose gold eternity band on the outer side of a rose gold pear ring creates a two-ring stack that reads as a complete designed set.

