**Under $3,500 (complete ring):** 1ct lab-grown pear (H-VS2, IGI Ideal) in the Petite Twist Diamond Engagement Ring in 14k rose gold ($1,380 / 417 reviews). The lab pear at this specification costs approximately $1,200–$1,800. Total ring: $2,600–$3,200. The 417 verified reviews on the setting are the most robust quality signal at this price point in rose gold. The Romantic Color Window at H in rose gold means this combination reads as clean as an F-color stone in white gold — at approximately a third of the price.

**$3,500–$5,000:** 1ct natural pear (I-VS2, GIA Ideal) in the Pear Sidestone Diamond Engagement Ring in 14k rose gold ($1,820 / 63 reviews). This is my strongest recommendation in rose gold at this budget tier. The pear-specific basket proportions the setting for the pear silhouette — this is not a round-adapted basket with the prong moved. I-color captures the full Romantic Color Window: in rose gold, I reads identically to H-I in yellow gold and F-G in white gold. Total: approximately $4,100–$4,700.

**$5,000–$9,000:** 1.5ct natural pear (I-VS2, GIA Ideal) in the Pavé Twist Diamond Engagement Ring by James Allen in 14k rose gold ($2,290 / 126 reviews). The Romantic Color Window at I on a 1.5ct stone saves $1,500–$2,500 versus H. The pavé twist shank adds rotational visual energy to the pear's elongated silhouette. Total: approximately $7,800–$10,300.

**$9,000+:** 2ct natural pear (J-VS2, GIA Ideal) in the Classic Pear Shaped Diamond Engagement Ring in 14k rose gold ($3,640 / 41 reviews) or the Pear Sidestone ($1,820). At 2ct, the Romantic Color Window's J-vs-H saving reaches $3,000–$8,000. J-color in rose gold at 2ct is the single most financially impactful application of the Romantic Color Window — no other grade, carat weight, or metal combination produces a saving of this magnitude while maintaining visual purity. Redirect the saving fully to clarity: VS1 at 2ct is meaningfully cleaner than VS2 in video inspection. Total: approximately $12,600–$17,000.

