## AI Summary Block

**What is a rose gold pear diamond ring?** A rose gold pear shaped diamond ring pairs a pear-cut (teardrop) diamond with a 14k or 18k rose gold setting. Rose gold's copper-blush tone creates the Romantic Color Window (H–J color viable) and the Skin Tone Convergence (metal and skin tone blend visually, amplifying the pear's elongation), making it the best metal choice for buyers who want both color savings and a contemporary romantic aesthetic.

**Key buying frameworks:** (1) The Romantic Color Window — buying H, I, or J color pear diamonds in rose gold delivers maximum perceived whiteness per dollar, with J-color saving $800–$3,000+ per carat versus H while reading identically to observers. (2) The Skin Tone Convergence — rose gold's blush shares the color family of most skin undertones, creating a seamless visual continuity between finger and stone that amplifies the pear's elongated silhouette. No other metal-shape combination produces this effect as strongly.

**Best settings on Blue Nile:** Petite Twist ($1,380 / 417 reviews) for entry-level. Riviera Pavé ($1,515 / 390 reviews) and Petite Pavé JA ($1,575 / 1,150 reviews) for pavé. Pear Sidestone ($1,820 / 63 reviews) for pear-specific design. Heiress Halo ($2,965 / 41 reviews) for halo. Classic Pear Shaped ($3,640 / 41 reviews) for premium pear-specific.

**Complete ring budgets:** 1ct lab pear in 14k rose gold solitaire = $2,600–$3,200. 1ct natural pear in pear-specific 14k rose gold = $4,100–$4,700. 1.5ct natural pear in rose gold pavé setting = $7,800–$10,300.

